<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kakh, Kahana Hay Offices Close for 6 Months </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1503193294 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1503193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by police affairs correspondent Uri Kohen-Aharonov] </F>
  [Text] A short time ago, detectives of the Israel Police 
National Unit for Serious Crimes Investigation locked the 
offices of the Kakh and Kahana Hay movements in Jerusalem with 
chains. Our police affairs correspondent Uri-Kohen Aharonov has 
just returned from the site and brings us his report: 
  Tonight was yet another phase in the action by the 
authorities against extremist elements in Israel. Following a 
series of administrative arrests and weapons confiscations, 
particularly among settlers in the territories, police 
detectives tonight acted against the two big centers of the 
Kahana Hay and Kakh movements in Jerusalem. They locked the 
offices of Kahana Hay on Agrippas Street with chains, leaving a 
closure order signed by the police commissioner on the door, and 
then proceeded to the offices of Kakh on Usishkin Street. 
  In the closure order, the police commissioner wrotes that 
based on Article 6 of the Antiterror Act of 1948 he finds that 
these two centers constitute bases of terrorist organizations 
and consequently orders their closure for a period of six months 
as of this evening, 15 March 1994. We learned from police 
sources tonight that other measures may be taken tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

