<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Musa Urges New Israeli `Attitude' Toward Settlers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1503194394 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 1830 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1503194394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa today said that the 
Middle East peace process will be in great peril unless Israel 
changes its attitude to Jewish settlers and takes bold steps to 
ensure the safety of Palestinians. 
  The foreign minister told REUTER that it is in the interest 
of all nations participating and interested in the Middle East 
negotiations to ensure that incidents similar to the Hebron 
massacre will never occur again. 
  Minister Musa said that Israel should abandon its current 
policy concerning settlers and settlements. Israel should also 
revise its security policy to provide protection for the 2 
million Palestinians who live under occupation, for those 
Palestinians are its responsibility, Musa pointed out. 
  The foreign minister said that Israel should abandon the 
policy that Israeli Army forces refrain from confronting armed 
settlers attacking Palestinians in the occupied territories. It 
is in everyone's interest that negotiations resume, but only 
once it is clear that measures, not yet taken, are in place to 
protect the Palestinians and deal with the settlers and 
settlements. 
  Minister Musa said that a UN Security Council resolution 
calling for an international presence to protect the 
Palestinians would not only pave the way for the resumption of 
talks between the PLO and Israel, but also breath life into the 
stalled Israeli-Syrian and Israeli-Jordanian talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-13587 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes051_a_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-051 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

