<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Senior Opposition Figure Urges UN To Extend Sanctions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1703115494 Paris AFP in English 1132 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1703115494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Irbil, Iraq, March 17, (AFP)--A senior member of the 
Iraqi opposition urged the UN Security Council Thursday to 
extend the sanctions on Iraq, saying Baghdad was far from 
complying with UN resolutions for a lifting of the embargo. 
  Two UN ceasefire resolutions were adopted at the end of the 
Gulf war in February 1991, calling on Iraq to destroy its 
weapons of mass destruction and to allow UN aid organisations 
free access across the country. 
  General Secretary of the main Iraqi opposition alliance 
Iraqi 
National Congress (INC), Dr. Ahmad Shalabi, told AFP: "The 
Iraqi regime is every day further away from implementing 
resolution 688" on allowing UN organisations access to carry aid 
programmes. 
  Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq 'Aziz began a new effort 
Wednesday to persuade the United Nations to lift the oil embargo 
imposed after the 1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
  In talks with French Ambassador Jean-Bernard Merimee, this 
month's Security Council chairman, 'Aziz called for an end to 
the embargo on Iraq since his country had complied with UN 
resolutions on disarming. 
  Shalabi, speaking from his headquarters in Salah al-Din, 
said 
a proposed option to lift the embargo only in Kurdish-controlled 
northern Iraq would be "problematical." 
  He said any such proposal would "raise strong opposition 
from 
Turkey's side" because of Ankara's continuing conflict with 
Kurds living in southeast Turkey. 
  He added that Turkey was the base for the UN operation 
Provide Comfort set up at the end of the Gulf war in February 
1991 to provide allied air cover for the Kurds in northern Iraq. 
  Kurdish leaders meanwhile said it would be a positive step 
if 
the UN lifted sanctions on northern Iraq. 
  The Security Council is expected to decide Thursday or 
Friday 
to keep the sanctions locked on Iraq, due to its view that 
Baghdad has not met all council resolution requirements, 
diplomats said. 
  Still a majority of the council's 15 members including 
France, China and Russia have asked that the council acknowledge 
Iraqi progress on disarmament, western diplomats said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

