<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nine Sentenced to Death for Attempt on Sidqi's Life </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1703072594 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0650 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1703072594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 17 Mar (MENA)--The Higher Military Court this 
morning passed the death sentence against nine defendants 
involved in an assassination attempt against Prime Minister Dr. 
'Atif Sidqi. Fifteen defendants, including six fugitives, were 
on trial in this case, which is better known as the "Vanguards 
of Conquest" case. 
  Three defendants were given a 15-year prison term with hard 
labor, one defendant was given a five-year prison term with hard 
labor, one was sentenced to three years in prison and fined 500 
Egyptian pounds, and another defendant was acquitted. 
  The defendants sentenced to death are: Fugitives 'Adil 
al-Sayyid 'Abd-al-Quddus, Tharwat Salah Shihatah, Yasir 'Ali 
al-Sirri, and Ahmad Isma'il 'Uthman, Salah al-Sayyid Sulyman, 
'Isam Muhammad 'Abd-al-Rahman, Nur-al-Din Sulayman Muhammad, 
Amin Isma'il Musaylihi, and Tariq 'Abd-al-Nabi al-Fahl. 
  The defendants sentenced to 15 years in prison with hard 
labor are: Tuhami Ahmad 'Abdallah, Muhammad 'Ali 'Ali Khalil, 
and Hani 'Abdallah 'Abd-al-Ra'uf. Defendant 'Abd-al-Rahman 
Hamid was given a five-year sentence with hard labor. Defendant 
Wahid Sa'd Fikri al-Mikkawi, a fugitive, was sentenced to three 
years in prison and fined 500 Egyptian pounds. Defendant 'Amr 
Husayn, also a fugitive, was acquitted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

