<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Efforts Under Way To Convene Arab Foreign Ministers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1603133394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1250 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1603133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 16 Mar (MENA)--Muhammad Subayh, Palestine 
National Council secretary general, has confirmed that intensive 
consultations are under way to hold a meeting of the five Arab 
countries involved in the Middle East peace process -- Egypt, 
Syria, Jordan, Palestine, and Lebanon -- in Cairo as soon as 
possible on the foreign minister level. 
  He said the aim of this meeting is to coordinate stances on 
resuming the Arab-Israeli peace talks and discuss the effects of 
the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre on the peace process. 
  In exclusive statements to MENA, Subayh said that Egypt is 
making intensive diplomatic moves with the United States, the 
Palestinians, and the Israelis to find a way out of the deadlock 
that the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations reached following the 
massacre perpetrated by the settlers in the al-Ibrahimi Mosque. 
  He noted that Egypt's efforts aim to convince Israeli Prime 
Minister Yitzhaq Rabin to show more flexibility toward the fair 
Palestinian demands to resume the peace negotiations. He noted 
that the Palestinian demands focus on the need to provide 
international protection for the Palestinian people, reduce the 
number of settlements, disarm the settlers, and release the 
Palestinian detainees. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

