<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Algeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zeroual Receives Message From Syrian Foreign Minister </TI></H3>
<H4>   Press Statement Issued </H4>
<F P=102> JN1703105094 Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network in 
Arabic 0515 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1703105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Press statement" issued in Algiers on 16 March] </F>
  [Text] Faruq al-Shar', foreign minister of the Syrian Arab 
Republic, visited Algeria on 3-4 Shawwal 1414 Hegira, 
corresponding to 15-16 March 1994, as a special envoy of His 
Excellency President Hafiz al-Asad of the Syrian Arab Republic. 
  During his stay in Algiers, he was received by His 
Excellency 
President Lamine Zeroual, who received a message from al-Shar' 
addressed to him by his brother His Excellency President Hafiz 
al-Asad of the Syrian Arab Republic. 
  A round of talks was held between Foreign Minister Mohamed 
Salah Dembri and Syrian Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar'. 
Delegations from the two countries took part in the talks. The 
two sides reviewed the overall fraternal ties between the two 
countries and their future prospects. They decided to revive 
the meetings of the Joint Syrian-Algerian Committee in Algiers 
in June 1994. 
  The two sides also exchanged views on Arab and international 
issues of common interest, foremost among which is the Middle 
East peace process, and the obstacles plaguing it due to Israeli 
intransigence, procrastination, and attempts to drag the 
concerned Arab sides into partial solutions. They agreed that 
the desired regional peace must be just and comprehensive and 
grounded in the relevant international legitimacy resolutions, 
particularly UN Security Council Resolutions 242, 338, and 425. 
  With regard to the occupied Syrian Golan, the two sides 
reasserted the need for Israel to effect a complete withdrawal 
from the occupied Syrian Golan in accordance with the relevant 
international legitimacy resolutions. They also demanded 
complete Israeli withdrawal from all other occupied Arab 
territories. The two sides also said that the restoration of 
the legitimate national rights of the Palestinian people must be 
guaranteed. 
  The two sides reiterated their condemnation of the heinous 
massacre committed by Israeli settlers at the holy Ibrahimi 
Mosque in Hebron, the occupied Palestinian West Bank. They 
appealed to the international community to shoulder its 
responsibilities in this regard to ensure the protection of the 
Palestinian people in the occupied Arab territories. 
  The two sides underscored that the drastic situation in the 
occupied Arab territories requires the termination of the 
Israeli occupation and the dismantlement of settlements in 
accordance with international legitimacy and the relevant UN 
resolutions. 
  The two sides examined the overall Arab situation and the 
sincere efforts required to rehabilitate Arab solidarity. They 
maintained that all efforts aimed at achieving a serious Arab 
reconciliation must be encouraged. The two sides also exchanged 
views on the topics listed on the agenda of the next ordinary 
session of the Arab League Ministerial Council. 
  Mindful of the importance of the issues pertaining to 
Mediterranean security and cooperation, and in light of European 
initiatives in this regard, the two sides urged an Arab 
initiative to call for a seminar to be attended by the Arab 
Mediterranean states for consultations and coordination, and 
also to crystallize joint positions toward these issues. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

