<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clarification of U.S. Stance on Jerusalem Requested </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1603160094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 16 Mar 94 p3 </F>
<F P=103> PM1603160094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "After Statements Attributed to </F>
Clinton, Arab Delegations Request Clarification on Status of 
Jerusalem"] 
  [Text] Cairo, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- In a new development 
related to the future of the Middle East peace process, the Arab 
parties concerned, the parties taking part in the negotiations, 
have sent an urgent memorandum to the U.S. Administration 
requesting official clarification regarding President Clinton's 
statement on Jerusalem in which he regarded both parts of the 
city as Israel's capital. The memorandum asked about the 
significance of that statement which ran contrary to a number of 
basic principles in the peace negotiations, in particular 
denoting a clear change in the U.S. line regarding the basis on 
which the Madrid peace conference was held, and which also ran 
contrary to the clear provisions of the UN Security Council 
resolutions, especially Resolutions 242 and 338 which stipulate 
that Israel should fully withdraw from all the Arab territories 
occupied in 1967 including Jerusalem. 
  Informed Arab and Palestinian sources in Cairo have stated 
that Washington's position on occupied Jerusalem requires a 
reconsideration of the Arab positions on the peace negotiations 
with a need for clear guarantees in this connection. 
  The sources said that the current intensive consultations 
with the PLO are not expected to yield clear results regarding 
resumption of the negotiations with Israel unless the issue of 
Jerusalem is resolved and guarantees are given that the issue of 
Jerusalem will still be on the agenda of the negotiations. The 
sources added that, in these consultations, the PLO declared its 
rejection of any change in the status of Jerusalem, emphasizing 
that the issue should be included in the provisions of the new 
[draft] agreement before the resumption of negotiations with 
Israel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-13639 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes052_l_94002" </HT>


