<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Palestinians, Settlers on Police Force </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1703073794 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0700 GMT 17 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1703073794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Faruq Amin, commander of the Palestinian police 
force designated to operate in the territories, said that the 
decision to deploy Palestinian policemen in Hebron must have the 
PLO's agreement, and calls for a separate agreement on that with 
Israel. 
  This view is shared by (Umayah) Tahbub, Hebron's former 
deputy police commander. Our correspondent Moti Amir notes that 
the two served in the Israel Police in the territories and 
resigned early in the intifadah, and now guard Faysal 
al-Husayni. They said that the proposal has not yet reached the 
PLO leadership in Tunis and that the Palestinians will not agree 
to deploy the policemen if they remain under Israeli command. 
  [Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew at 0600 GMT on 17 March 
carries 
a live telephone interview with Ziyad Abu-Zayyad, a member of 
the Palestinian advisory council, by Itay Engel and Mikhal 
Gazit, on the same issue. Abu-Zayyad thinks "the proposal can 
serve as a basis for trying to reach a wording acceptable to 
both sides, but to deploy the Palestinian police force which 
existed prior to the intifadah and say that it means the 
Palestinians are responsible for their own defense will not 
work."] 
  Hebron's Jewish settlers are furious about the reports that 
the government will consider the deployment of Palestinian 
policemen in Hebron. They said such a move would lead to 
continued bloodshed in the area. A member of the Mate Binyamin 
Regional Council told our correspondent Gil Litman that the 
names of many officers and soldiers in the military reserve are 
listed in their offices and if Palestinian policemen come to 
Hebron they will be recruited to defend Hebron against these 
policemen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

