<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin, Pope Meet; 'Arafat Urged To Return to Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1703145194 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 1330 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1703145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Udi Segal] </F>
  [Text] The meeting between Prime Minister and the pope 
ended a short while ago. Prime Minister Rabin met privately 
with Pope John Paul II. The two men held a relatively short 
45-minute meeting. Rabin condemned the Hebron massacre and asked 
the pope to use his religious and moral authority to call on all 
parties to resume the negotiations. The pope, for his part, 
said that he hoped for peace in the Middle East before the year 
2000. The pope briefed Rabin on his plans to visit Lebanon. As 
for the possibility of coming to Israel, the pope said that he 
looked forward to visiting Jerusalem, but did not mention any 
dates. 
  Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin presented the pope with an 
ancient vase, approximately 3,000 years old, and said that he 
hoped the pope would be able to preserve the vase for another 
3,000 years. 
  Several minutes ago, we asked Prime Minister Rabin several 
questions pertaining to the political process. The prime 
minister replied that since he had just completed his visit to 
Washington, it was still too early to speculate on the chances 
for progress in the negotiations. As for the evacuation of the 
Jewish residents of Hebron, Rabin said: Although we will not 
reopen the Oslo and Cairo agreements we will definitely take 
more steps to guarantee the security of the Palestinians in the 
territories. The prime minister described the design of the 
Jewish settlement in Hebron as stupid. 
  [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 1400 GMT on 17 March, 
in 
a report on Rabin's meeting with the pope, adds the following: 
"Mr. Rabin told the pope he is eagerly looking forward to his 
visit to Israel." "Our correspondent in Rome Yosi Bar reports 
that Mr. Rabin promised the pope to bring peace and prosperity 
to the Holy Land. Following the meeting Mr. Rabin said the pope 
can provide spiritual and religious help to facilitate the peace 
negotiations. 
  "The Vatican's envoy stated that the pope has called on 
Yasir 
'Arafat to return to the peace negotiations with Israel. The 
envoy said that during his meeting with Yasir 'Arafat in Tunis 
he conveyed to him the pope's support for the rights of the 
Palestinians. The envoy -- who serves as the Vatican's foreign 
minister -- also stated that the Holy See is not mediating 
between the sides."] 

</TEXT>

