<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   League Chief Receives Qaddumi Message, Envoy Kamal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1703122094 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1143 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1703122094 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 17 Mar (MENA)--Arab League Secretary General 
Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid today received a written message from 
Faruq Qaddumi, the head of the PLO's Political Department. The 
message concerns the latest developments in the talks with 
Israel in light of Arab moves to ensure security for the 
Palestinians in the occupied territories, disarm the settlers, 
and obtain a Security Council resolution condemning the Israeli 
massacre at the al-Ibrahimi Mosque. This can be achieved by 
providing international protection and by tangible measures by 
the Israelis to ensure security for the Palestinians. 
  Sa'id Kamal, the Palestinian ambassador in Cairo, noted that 
he and Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid discussed U.S. President Bill Clinton's 
recent remarks about the status of Jerusalem. He noted that the 
Arab League secretary general promised to take the necessary 
measures to back the Palestinian side should the talks with 
Israel resume, especially with regard to the call for disbanding 
the settlements and not recognizing Israel's measures on 
Jerusalem. 
  Kamal added that he briefed Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid on the recent 
contacts held between PLO officials and Arab and international 
officials, including the foreign ministers of Egypt, Syria, and 
Lebanon. He pointed out that these contacts dealt with the 
future of the Middle East peace process following the massacre. 
He noted that a meeting among officials from the cordon states 
[Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, and Egypt and the PLO] is likely to be 
held on the sidelines of the Arab League ministerial meeting in 
Cairo on 26 March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

