<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reform Official Warns Against `Foreign' Partition Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN1703160294 Baghdad INA in Arabic 1250 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN1703160294 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sanaa, 17 Mar (INA)--Shaykh 'Abd-al-Majid 
al-Zindani, member of the Yemeni Presidential Council, has 
warned against a foreign and Zionist scheme to partition Yemen 
into several statelets in order to make it easier to control its 
oil wealth and strategic location, especially the strait of Bab 
el Mandeb in the Red Sea. 
  In statements before Yemeni military units broadcast today, 
al-Zindani stressed that the scheme to divide Yemen aims at 
establishing several statelets by inciting tribal and sectarian 
dissension and paralyzing the state's official institutions in 
order to drag the Yemeni people into infighting. 
  He said this scheme is part of a colonialist course that 
targets not just Yemen, but every Arab attempt to forge a better 
future in the region. He indicated that anti-Arab foreign 
forces do not want to see Arabs and Muslims become capable of 
making any advancement and seek to render them desperate about 
any chances of progress. 
  He recalled that the West wagered on fighting among the 
parties to the Yemeni coalition immediately after the elections, 
especially between the Islamists -- the Yemeni Reform Grouping 
-- and the Yemeni Socialist Party. 
  Al-Zindani revealed that one of the objectives of the 
foreign 
scheme against Yemen is to control or lease the strait of Bab el 
Mandeb and to establish weak statelets. He indicated that when 
the Yemenis are unified and strong, foreign powers find it 
extremely difficult to impose their humiliating conditions. 
  The statements by al-Zindani, who is a prominent member of 
the Yemeni Reform Grouping under Shaykh 'Abdallah Bin-Husayn 
al-Ahmar, are part of the warnings that the grouping issued to 
the General People's Congress and the Yemeni Socialist Party on 
the gravity of the continued crisis and its effects on the 
future of Yemen's unity. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

