<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Son of Parliament Speaker Escapes Assassination Bid </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1603152894 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 16 Mar 94 
pp1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1603152894 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hammud Munsir: "Al-Ahmar's Son Escapes </F>
Assassination Attempt in Ambush Near Sanaa"] 
  [Excerpt] Sanaa -- Shaykh Husayn 'Abdallah al-Ahmar, son of 
Shaykh 'Abdallah Bin-Husayn al-Ahmar, speaker of the Yemeni 
House of Representatives, chairman of the Higher Committee of 
the Yemeni Reform Grouping [YRG], and chieftain of the Hashid 
tribes, escaped an assassination attempt at 0900 yesterday as he 
was returning to Sanaa from the northern Khamr region, 
considered to be the main center of the Hashid tribes. Only one 
of his guards was wounded in the attempt. 
  In a statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT, a source close to 
Shaykh 
al-Ahmar said the attempt occurred in an ambush on the northern 
road outside the town of 'Umran 60 km from Sanaa when the car of 
a group of tribal gunmen intercepted and collided with the first 
car in Shaykh al-Ahmar's motorcade which had already overtaken 
it. 
  As the motorcade continued its journey with the shaykh's car 
between two guard cars, a hail of bullets rained on the 
motorcade from both sides of the road. The guards returned fire 
and although the attackers concentrated their fire on the 
shaykh's Mercedes, he was not hurt at all and the attackers fled. 
  The attempt does not seem to have any political significance 
and is not linked to the current Yemeni crisis. There is 
speculation that it might be related to tribal differences. The 
source said that all members of the attacking group were 
identified as tribal men but he did not say to which tribes they 
belonged. He said that they were not from the area where the 
incident occurred and that they came from other areas. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

