<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Syrian Official Urges U.S. Pressure on Israel </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1803095194 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 17 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM1803095194 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by al-Ustuwani: "Damascus Urges Washington To </F>
Resolve Current Peace Process Impasse"] 
  [Excerpt] Damascus -- Syria yesterday urged the United 
States to act effectively to resolve the current peace process 
impasse. A Syrian official has told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that 
Israel caused that impasse and that only international and U.S. 
action can resolve it by putting pressure on Israel to return to 
the basis on which the peace initiative was founded, and by 
doing that on all fronts without putting pressure on the 
Palestinians to implement the Oslo agreement, because that 
agreement has been proven to be a failure and is unacceptable to 
the Palestinian people. 
  The source said that there was no alternative to an Israeli 
declaration of willingness to withdraw completely from all the 
occupied territories in order to ensure the success of the 
negotiations. He added that the settlements issue has become an 
urgent matter which must be discussed to determine the fate of 
the settlers and to work for their evacuation from the occupied 
Arab territories because they have become a daily threat and 
danger to the Palestinian people, as Hebron's al-Ibrahimi mosque 
massacre demonstrated. 
  The official said that the aim of Israeli Prime Minister 
Yitzhaq Rabin's visit to the United States was to make 
Washington pressure the Palestinians into completing the 
separate peace agreement to enable the occupation authorities to 
impose the settlements for five more years at least, and also to 
paralayze the Security Council and prevent it passing an 
anti-Israel resolution and providing protection for the 
Palestinian people. 
  He said that Syria was still interested in peace and had 
from 
the beginning responded to the prerequisites of the peace 
process, but Israel was placing many obstacles in the way of any 
progress. There will be no progress, he said, as long as Israel 
continues to pursue a policy which does not serve peace in any 
way. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

