<H3> <TI>   Government, Factions To Hold Talks in Nairobi </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  EA1403195894 Khartoum SUNA in Arabic 1605 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> EA1403195894 </F>
<F P=104>  Khartoum SUNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Khartoum, 14 Mar (SUNA) -- Lieutenant General 'Umar 
al-Bashir, the president of the Republic, will leave for the 
Kenyan capital, Nairobi, on 16 March at the invitation of Kenyan 
President Daniel arap Moi. SUNA has learned that the Kenyan 
president had invited Lt. Gen. al-Bashir to brief him on the 
meeting of the Intergovernmental Authority on Drought and 
Development [IGADD] presidents held in Nairobi on 9 March with a 
view to preparing for a round of peace talks under the 
sponsorship of the IGADD grouping. There will also be 
consultations between the two presidents on the agenda of the 
round due to start in Nairobi on 17 March. 
  SUNA has learned that Mr. Muhammad al-Amin Khalifah, 
chairman 
of the Transitional National Assembly, will lead the government 
delegation to the talks in Nairobi. The government delegation 
will also include the official spokesman of the delegation of 
the government. The delegation of Garang's faction will be 
headed by Silva Kiir Mayar Dit. Other members of the delegation 
will be Deng Alor and Husayn (Bak). The United Faction and 
other dissident factions have also been invited to participate 
in the negotiations. 
  [Omdurman Republic of Sudan Radio Network in Arabic at 1700 
GMT on 14 March, in a related report, adds the following: "The 
government delegation will also include Dr. 'Ali al-Hajj 
Muhammad, the minister at the Office of Federal Rule and the 
official spokesman of the government delegation to the 
negotiations; Dr. Ahmad Ibrahim al-Tahir, minister of state and 
legal adviser to the president of the Republic; and others. The 
delegation of rebel John Garang will be led by Silva Kiir Mayar 
Dit. The delegation will also include Deng Alor and Justin 
Yaak. The United Faction and other dissident factions have also 
been invited to participate in this round of negotiations."] 

