<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agree To Peace Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB1703175094 Paris AFP in English 1657 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1703175094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nairobi, March 17 (AFP) -- Sudan's Islamic 
fundamentalist government and mainly Christian and black 
southern rebels agreed Thursday [17 March] to launch peace talks 
aimed at ending a decades-old civil war. 
  The agreement came after hours of closed-door talks here 
between Sudanese President 'Umar al-Bashir and the presidents of 
Kenya, Ethiopia and Uganda, who also met leaders of two rival 
factions of the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA). 
  "The government of Sudan and the SPLA factions have stated 
their readiness to immediately embark on peace negotiations," 
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi said. 
  The six-nation regional organisation, the Intergovernmental 
Authority on Drought and Development (IGADD), has named Kenya, 
Ethiopia, Uganda and Eritrea to spearhead a new initiative to 
bring peace to famine-hit Sudan. 
  The agreement stopped short of declaring a ceasefire in 
southern Sudan, where the government has taken advantage of 
tribal divisions in the SPLA to launch a new offensive aimed at 
crushing the southern rebellion. 
  But the IGADD presidents said in a press statement that the 
warring parties had agreed to "desist from esclating hostilities 
... in order to create a conducive atmosphere for the 
negotiations." 
  "The root causes of the conflict are so complex that 
previous 
peace conference have failed to arrive at a peaceful solution," 
Moi told his fellow heads of state and rebel leaders in a brief 
open session after the meetings. 
  "We must be prepared to give peace a chance," Moi said, 
stressing that Africans had to play a more active role in 
solving their problems instead of waiting for outside 
initiatives. 
  He said the forthcoming negotiations would try to reach "a 
comprehensive negotiated settlement and urged all sides to allow 
relief supplies into southern Sudan, where millions depend on 
food aid. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-13690 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes053_g_94004" </HT>


