<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Khatib on Rabin U.S. Visit, Clinton Remarks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1803075894 Cairo Voice of the Arabs in Arabic 0610 GMT 18 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1803075894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Voice of the Arabs </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Ghassan al-Khatib, a member of the </F>
Palestinian delegation to the peace talks, in Jerusalem, by 
Fayiz al-Miliji, in Cairo, date not given; from the "Dialogue 
From Afar" program--recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [Al-Miliji] The visit to the United States by 
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin has triggered Arab 
reaction. How do the Palestinians view the visit and where do 
they stand on the results that have appeared? 
  [Al-Khatib] First, not all the results of the visit have 
appeared. It is clear that some issues were discussed but not 
publicized. The two sides announced that they agreed on several 
issues, which have not been publicized fully. So it is hard to 
make a final judgment on the outcome of the visit. The results 
announced so far fall short of meeting the minimum demands or 
needs that the Palestinian leadership put forward as urgent 
prerequisites for resuming negotiations and guaranteeing their 
success should they be resumed soon. [passage omitted] 
  The U.S. Government has unfortunately failed to cooperate in 
convincing Israel to respond to these demands. Hence, the 
Israelis are not serious and the U.S. stance backs them. 
  [Al-Miliji] You said that the Palestinian leadership 
conveyed 
these demands. Were they conveyed during the visit to Tunisia 
by Dennis Ross, the U.S. coordinator of the Arab-Israeli peace 
negotiations? 
  [Al-Khatib] These demands were conveyed earlier, through the 
Palestinian delegation that visited Washington. 
  [Al-Miliji] The delegation that Dr. Sa'ib 'Urayqat led? 
  [Al-Khatib] Yes. The day after the massacre a meeting was 
held between Dr. 'Urayqat and representatives of the U.S. State 
Department. The demands were conveyed during that meeting. 
They were also conveyed to Dennis Ross, during his visit to 
Tunisia, and were directly conveyed to Rabin more than once. 
  [Al-Miliji] Has the Palestinian leadership received no 
response? 
  [Al-Khatib] It received a reply from Rabin saying that the 
demands concerning settlement cannot be met because this would 
violate the Oslo agreement. He added that the Israeli 
Government would take a set of measures to curb the settlers' 
terrorist activity. These measures were announced later 
following a meeting of the Israeli inner cabinet. 
  [Al-Miliji] What about the U.S. response? 
  [Al-Khatib] There is no direct or material U.S. response. 
The 
U.S. Administration has shown no understanding of these demands. 
But there was no direct rejection. 
  [Al-Miliji] Some believe the PLO can resume the peace 
negotiations and submit these demands for discussion at the 
negotiating table. What do you think? 
  [Al-Khatib] I do not believe this approach will work. To 
return to negotiations without defining the basics that take 
note of the recent tragic experience will again involve us in 
negotiations that waste time uselessly. To make the resumption 
of talks feasible, the bases of the negotiations must be amended 
so that the issues pertaining to settlements can be addressed. 
  [Al-Miliji] We now turn to another topic, that is, honorable 
Jerusalem and the U.S. President's remarks that viewed it as the 
united capital of Israel. This is the first time a U.S. 
President has made such a statement. Do the Palestinians have 
an official stance on that statement? 
  [Al-Khatib] Certainly. First, it constitutes a backing down 
on the previous U.S. stance. In the context of preparations for 
talks, as well as during the talks, the U.S. stance provided for 
postponing discussion of the issue of Jerusalem until the final 
stage. Second, this stance violates and is inconsistent with 
the UN Security Council resolutions and international 
legitimacy. We have recently noticed that the United States has 
tended to take Israel's side. We believe that this complicates 
rather than facilitates negotiations. We believe there should 
be critical reaction, not only by the Palestinians, but also by 
the Arab and Muslim parties, since Jerusalem concerns all Arab 
and Muslim brothers. 
  [Al-Miliji] We thank Ghassan al-Khatib. 
  [Al-Khatib] Thank you. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-13710 </DOCNO>
