<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Figures Assail U.S. Stance in Security Council </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1703165994 Jerusalem AL-QUDS in Arabic 17 Mar 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> TA1703165994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem AL-QUDS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By 'Izzat Daraghmah] </F>
  [Excerpt] Jerusalem -- Palestinian leaders and 
personalities in the occupied territories have described the 
U.S. position on the adoption of a Security Council resolution 
condemning the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre on 25 February as a 
position "that is biased and dishonest. The United States 
cannot be accepted as a sponsor of the negotiating process 
because it defends Israel, its positions, and justifications. 
The responsibility for this massacre falls on the Israeli 
Government and Army, which controls all the Palestinian 
territories." 
  Dr. Sa'ib 'Urayqat, head of the Palestinian negotiating 
delegation in Washington, said: The United States cannot be a 
sponsor of the conference because this requires honesty and 
credibility, and this is what the current U.S. Administration 
lacks. 
  'Urayqat added that delay on the issuing of and voting on a 
resolution condemning the massacre has been caused by the 
position of the United States, Israel's strategic ally. On the 
first day of the massacre, the United States said: "We will see 
you at the Security Council if you are insisting that it issue a 
resolution on the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre". However, the 
United States backed down as a result of Israel's recommendation 
and linked the issuance of that resolution with the PLO's 
consent to resume the talks. 
  For her part, Dr. Hanan 'Ashrawi, head of the first 
Palestinian juristic organization for monitoring the Palestinian 
authority on human rights, considered the U.S. position as an 
attempt at blackmail by using the Security Council resolution as 
a means to pressure the PLO to return to the talks. 
  She added: The sign that is more serious than all this is 
that, as we are constantly aware, U.S. intervention has always 
been in the Israeli interest and against the Arabs in order to 
give Israel the opportunity to dictate what it wants and to 
protect Israel from the consequences of its actions. Even more 
serious than this is that there are real indications of a shift 
in U.S. policy regarding Jerusalem. I believe that if the 
United States changes the Security Council draft resolution, 
whereby that resolution will become ineffective and useless with 
respect to Jerusalem, and if it uses the veto, this will be 
proof of a grave U.S. challenge to UN resolutions and of a 
fundamental shift in respect to Jerusalem. This will greatly 
alter the credibility of the United States as a sponsor, because 
then it cannot be a neutral sponsor. 
  'Ashrawi stressed that if the Security Council resolution is 
similar to previous ones, there will be no need to issue a new 
resolution. She said that the United States itself is in favor 
of this sort of approach and attitude. 
  Dr. Haydar 'Abd-al-Shafi, head of the reformers in the PLO, 
said: The Security Council resolution stemming from the criminal 
act of the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre must contain certain 
requirements, most important of which are providing protection 
for the Palestinian people and achieving credibility. The 
Palestinian people are well aware of this. 
  For his part, Radwan Abu-'Ayyash, head of the Palestinian 
radio and television organization and advisory member of the 
Palestinian delegation, said: We believe that the massacre that 
took place in Hebron represents a grave and bloody threat to the 
safety and security of the Palestinian people in the occupied 
territories. This requires international protection and 
consideration of the PLO's position calling for the presence of 
an international protection able to curb the Jewish settlers and 
extremists, because this has become very necessary. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

