<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   GUARDIAN Reveals Plans for `Surprise' Military Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN1803070794 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1715 GMT 17 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1803070794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Huda al-Husayni from London] </F>
  [Excerpt] THE GUARDIAN today expects Iraq to launch a 
surprise military strike. The British newspaper says: Iraqi 
President Saddam Husayn, who has been quiet for a year, will 
return very soon to his military strategy and deal a lightening 
strike against Western forces inside and outside Iraq. The 
newspaper says: The Iraqi president's patience is coming to an 
end as a result of the embargo imposed by the United Nations 
since his invasion of Kuwait and the exacerbating economic 
situation. This, the paper adds, will prompt him to carry out a 
new bloody adventure. 
  THE GUARDIAN adds that it has been expected recently that 
this adventure will be in the form of a military strike or 
threat against the State of Kuwait or Kurdistan and that this 
strike will take place next week. THE GUARDIAN bases its 
expectations on reports that Iraq is beefing up its Armed Forces 
and deploying them in the North and the South. As a result of 
this, the paper adds, Iraqis are storing food supplies and 
drawing large amounts of money from banks. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

