<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Connections of Church Bombing Culprits Cited </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2003075294 Beirut Voice of Lebanon in Arabic 0615 GMT 20 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2003075294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut Voice of Lebanon </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Citing one of the top three leaders [president, 
Chamber speaker, prime minister], the newspaper AL-HAYAH reports 
today that the network involved in the bombing of the Sayyidat 
al-Najat Church has direct links to Israel, noting that the 
network leaders are linked to a local militia. The paper says 
that the network leaders had often visited the security strip 
and a European capital. 
  According to the top leader, AL-HAYAH says that the 
investigations into the incident will inevitably confirm whether 
party and militia leaders are involved in the bombing, 
particularly since the group leader, who probably has escaped to 
the Jazzin area in the security strip, was in charge of security 
affairs in a local influential militia in the Kasrawan region. 
The group leader, according to AL-HAYAH, is a relative of a 
prominent party leader. 
  AL-HAYAH also cites official sources as saying that the 
initial stage of the preparation of the explosives was conducted 
in Sinn al-Fil before the culprits moved to the Zuq area. The 
culprits then used a party center, which has often been raided, 
to assemble the explosive devices before planting them in the 
church. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

