<H3> <TI>   Iranian Envoy To Visit Islamabad To Discuss Kashmir </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1803054594 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network in Urdu 0200 
GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1803054594 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Urdu </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pakistan has greatly succeeded in attracting world 
public opinion toward atrocities being committed by India in 
occupied Kashmir. This was stated by Foreign Secretary 
Shaharyar Khan while addressing a function in Lahore last night. 
He categorically stated that Pakistan has not withdrawn its 
resolution on Kashmir from the UN Human Rights Commission and 
has agreed only to defer the voting on the resolution, which is 
still effective and can be taken up at any time. 
  Appreciating the Islamic Conference Organization's [ICO's] 
support on the Kashmir issue, the foreign secretary said the ICO 
has unanimously approved resolutions on Kashmir five times in 
the past. These resolutions have greatly helped to generate 
sympathies for the Kashmiri people, who are waging a struggle to 
achieve their right of self-determination. 
  Shaharyar Khan said India cannot renege on its promise to 
allow a visit of a mission comprised of envoys from Islamic 
countries to assess the repression committed in occupied 
Kashmir. He disclosed that Iranian President 
Hashemi-Rafsanjani's special emissary is arriving in Islamabad 
today to discuss this particular issue. He said India's 
acceptance of this proposal is on record. 

</TEXT>

