<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Kuwait </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister: Budget Delaying Missile Purchase </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2003084494 Kuwait KUNA in Arabic 0755 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2003084494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait KUNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kuwait, 20 Mar--In an interview published here 
today, Defense Minister Shaykh 'Ali Sabah al-Salim al-Sabah 
ruled out that the ministry would review or withdraw from 
purchasing a number of U.S. Patriot missiles. 
  The defense minister's statement to the AL-ANBA' newspaper 
followed reports on the dependence of the U.S. Army on new 
missiles, cancelling its dependence on the Patriot in air 
defense missions. The Kuwaiti defense minister clarified to the 
newspaper that the new type of missiles were still being tested 
for their effectiveness. He added that the upgraded Patriot 
missile that was being used by the U.S. Army would be the same 
type used by Kuwaiti forces. 
  Shaykh 'Ali al-Sabah justified the delay in purchasing these 
missiles and other types of armament and military equipment for 
the forces by citing a delay in the approval of the military 
budget. He also added that a reduction in the number of American 
technicians working in the various army units came after they 
had concluded their duties. He said they had completed their 
business and that their contracts had ended in a normal manner. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

