<H3> <TI>   General People's Congress Assails al-Bid Statement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN1903155794 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1200 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1903155794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by "responsible source" at the General People's </F>
Congress General Committee to SABA'; date not given] 
  [Excerpt] We were all surprised by the statement by brother 
'Ali Salim al-Bid, Presidential Council vice chairman, to the 
United Arab Emirates' English-language newspaper, THE GULF NEWS, 
on 16 March. These statements were reported by news agencies and 
some world radios. Al-Bid said in that interview that if a 
plebiscite is held in the southern and eastern provinces, the 
majority will prefer returning to conditions that existed before 
22 May 1990. This is secession. 
  We regret this statement by the Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP] 
secretary general. It casts doubt on the patriotism of citizens 
in the southern and eastern provinces and on their adherence to 
unity. We express our absolute rejection of this accusation, 
which we consider to be directed against all the Yemeni people. 
We consider this statement an accusation of the YSP itself 
because we firmly believe most YSP members adhere to, and will 
continue to adhere to, unity and democracy. The forces of 
defection and secession that have influence inside the YSP draw 
strength from foreign forces that target unity and democracy in 
Yemen. We believe this statement is not only a serious 
accusation directed against the the Yemeni people, particularly 
the majority of YSP members, but also a statement with very 
serious dimensions. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

