<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Ban Issue of London-Based Daily </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1803144594 Paris AFP in English 1343 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1803144594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, March 18 (AFP)--The Egyptian authorities 
banned sales of the Friday edition of the London-based 
Arabic-language daily AL-HAYAT because it reported the execution 
of the two fundamentalist soldiers accused of plotting to kill 
Mubarak, reliable sources said. 
  The Egyptian media did not mention the executions or the 
trial of the two Islamic militants. 
  AL-HAYAT is edited in London and distributed in Cairo and 
other Arab capitals. 
  Last year the authorities criticised the newspaper several 
times, notably in connection with its publication of an 
interview with Shaykh Umar 'Abd-al-Rahman, whom the Islamic 
militants regard as their spiritual leader. 

</TEXT>

