<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Hebron Mayor Comments on Resolution 904 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1903090394 Cairo Voice of the Arabs in Arabic 0610 GMT 19 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1903090394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Voice of the Arabs </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with former Hebron Mayor Mustafa </F>
al-Natshah in Hebron by Ashraf 'Abd-al-'Aziz in Cairo, date not 
given; from the "Dialogue From Afar" program--recorded] 
  [Text] ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Mr. al-Natshah, good morning and 
welcome to the Voice of the Arabs. 
  [Al-Natshah] Good morning, thank you. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] How do you see the UN Security Council's 
resolution concerning the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre? 
  [Al-Natshah] I can say that the issue of protection is a 
just 
demand. We welcome the resolution. I hope that it will be 
implemented completely and will ensure real protection for the 
citizens against the settlers' attacks and the Israeli army's 
actions as well. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] The resolution failed to refer to the issue 
of Jerusalem. How do you explain this? 
  [Al-Natshah] We regret that the issue of Jerusalem was not 
included in the resolution. This, perhaps, is due to U.S. 
pressure. It represents a serious shift in the U.S. position. 
The United States has often voted in the past in favor of 
considering Jerusalem an integral part of the occupied 
territories. But it is the U.S. pressure that has now played a 
role in omitting the issue of Jerusalem from the resolution. 
All the people have voiced their indignation over this stand. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Can we expect that the UN Security Council 
resolution, which condemns the massacre, will pave the way for 
the resumption of the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks? 
  [Al-Natshah] I believe that this could help the PLO return 
to 
the negotiations, and I also believe that the Israeli 
authorities might respond to other demands. We also hope that 
the Israeli authorities will also respond to the resolution and 
to the other demands set by the PLO as a condition for returning 
to the negotiations. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] The Security Council has called for 
providing 
a temporary international presence to ensure protection for 
Palestinian citizens. What do you think of this presence? 
  [Al-Natshah] The word presence does not mean international 
forces like those that are deployed in Bosnia-Herzegovina or 
Somalia. It is rather the presence of unarmed UN observers to 
intervene in one way or another if attacks take place. This 
does not mean armed protection as is the case in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. It is just few observers in the occupied 
territories who would do their best to prevent any attack on the 
citizens. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] The Israeli Government is currently studying 
the idea of assembling all the Jewish settlements in an area in 
the town of Hebron. Could this represent a solution to 
guarantee Palestinian security? 
  [Al-Natshah] The attempt to assemble them in Hebron is not a 
solution. Because the presence of settlements in the heart of 
Hebron has split it in half and has obstructed communications 
between the southern part and its western and northern parts, 
particularly during Fridays and Saturdays when the army bans 
traffic between the two parts of the town. Therefore, the best 
practical step in this issue is to withdraw the citizens from 
Hebron to another settlement as a temporary solution until a 
final solution is worked out, namely dismantling the settlements 
and withdrawing the settlers from the occupied Palestinian land. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] What more do you need from the international 
community after the Security Council resolution, which condemned 
the massacre? 
  [Al-Natshah] We call on the international community to help 
place the issue of settlements at the top of the agenda of the 
negotiations. This is a basic demand that has also been 
prompted by the Hebron massacre. It is a fundamental, pressing 
demand and should not be delayed. Because the presence of 
settlements during any transitional stage would be an explosive 
issue that might destroy any agreement. This kind of massacre 
could recur in the future in other areas and could torpedo any 
agreement. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Thank you very much. 
  [Al-Natshah] You are welcome. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

