<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin Briefs Cabinet on Plans for Talks' Resumption </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2003125794 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1200 GMT 20 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2003125794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At today's cabinet session, Prime Minister Yitzhaq 
Rabin briefed the ministers on the steps being taken prior to 
the resumption of the peace talks. Minister Shim'on Shetrit 
complained that Israel's position on the status of Jerusalem is 
unclear. Mr. Rabin replied that Jerusalem is not an issue for 
negotiations at this time, adding that Israel has made no 
concessions whatsoever on this matter. Rabin noted that he had 
underestimated the extent of the widespread support among 
settler circles for the Hebron massacre. The prime minister 
said that the deliberations of the Shamgar Commission, which is 
investigating the Hebron massacre, undermine the IDF's [Israel 
Defense Forces] credibility in the eyes of the public. 
  Our political correspondent Shlomo Raz reports that the 
cabinet also discussed the continuation of the closure on the 
territories. One of the possibilities discussed was extending 
the closure on the territories until after the holidays. Police 
Minister Moshe Shahal supports this proposal. 

</TEXT>

