<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres Sees Positive Change in U.S. Jerusalem Stance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1903095994 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0805 GMT 19 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1903095994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres by </F>
Eytan Almog; recorded on 19 March] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Almog] Mr. Peres, in last 
night's vote in the UN Security Council we still enjoyed U.S. 
support regarding Jerusalem's status as the united capital of 
Israel which is under complete Israeli sovereignty. Is the word 
still appropriately placed in the above sentence? 
  [Peres] I do not want to play down the UNSC resolution. 
There is a change, however, in the U.S. position -- and I think 
it is a change somewhat for the better. To date the United 
States on two occasions voted in favor of including Jerusalem in 
the definition of the occupied territories. This time it 
abstained, and the reason for this is that had it voted against, 
it would have in fact vetoed the entire resolution and the 
Security Council would have been left without any resolution. 
One of the reasons which caused the United States to abstain is 
that the Declaration of Principles does not even mention 
Jerusalem. The present U.S. Administration has also taken upon 
itself severe restrictions regarding Jerusalem. The solution 
which the United States thought most appropriate in the present 
case was not to vote in favor -- as in the past -- but rather to 
abstain. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

