<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   King, Others React to Security Council Resolution </TI></H3>
<H4>   Further al-'Alani Comments on Resolution </H4>
<F P=102> NC2103095294 Cairo Voice of the Arabs in Arabic 0610 GMT 21 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2103095294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Voice of the Arabs </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Information Minister Dr. Jawad al-'Anani, in </F>
Amman, by Ashraf 'Abd-al-'Aziz, in Cairo, date not given; from 
the "Dialogue From Afar" program--recorded] 
  [Text] ['Abd-al-'Aziz] What is Jordan's impression of and 
stance on the Security Council's resolution denouncing the 
al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre? 
  [Al-'Anani] The Jordanian Government met on Saturday morning 
following the announcement and held an extensive debate on it. 
The government decided that the resolution, Security Council 
Resolution 904, is generally positive, contains some points that 
we regard as positive, and advances the issue it dealt with, 
primarily the protection of the Palestinian people and their 
security on their national soil. 
  We found the clear reference to the occupied Arab 
territories, including Arab Jerusalem, to be positive. We 
believe that the clear and strong denunciation of the massacre 
was one of the positive points. The note on the need for Israel 
to apply the Fourth Geneva Convention of 1945 in all occupied 
Arab territories, including east Jerusalem, was a positive point 
in that resolution. We believe it is now necessary to adopt 
practical measures to translate the resolution into a tangible 
reality, because the Jordanian Government notes with extreme 
concern that the injuries and killings in the occupied Arab land 
since the massacre on 25 February are increasing considerably. 
We must take measures that will guarantee the protection and 
security of the Palestinian people. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] After Security Council Resolution 904 
denouncing the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre was passed, is it now 
certain that the peace process will be resumed? 
  [Al-'Anani] You know the massacre happened while 
consultations were under way among the heads of the delegations 
of the countries participating in the negotiating process. But 
after consultations among themselves, these delegations made a 
collective decision on the need to suspend the negotiations 
until measures are decided following the horrible carnage in 
Hebron. We believe the resolution has contributed to creating a 
favorable atmosphere for resuming negotiations to reach a 
comprehensive, just, and durable solution based on UN 
Resolutions 242 and 338 as well as 425, which concerns Lebanon. 
Jordan believes the road is now open to return to negotiations 
but, as happened before, the decision [to resume talks] must 
come after coordination among the negotiating countries or among 
the foreign ministers of the cordon states that held previous 
meetings in which Egypt participated, represented by its foreign 
minister. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Where does the Jordanian-Israeli track 
stand? 
  [Al-'Anani] The Jordanian-Israeli track of the negotiations 
at the end of the consultations among the delegation heads in 
Washington almost reached the point of formulating some topics 
on the agenda and a detailed subagenda was agreed for 
negotiating these topics. On water, energy, and the 
environment, there was agreement on most of the topics that must 
be discussed in this framework. But security and the borders, 
as some of the key topics on the agenda, on the basis of which 
an agreement will be reached on the mechanism of Israel's 
withdrawal from the Jordanian occupied territories, are not yet 
settled. Besides, the issue of refugees still needs discussion. 
We can say that there is an atmosphere that calls for optimism 
about progress but we cannot say that any (?positive) progress 
has occurred on substantial issues. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] What is your [words indistinct] Arab 
coordination, especially with the resumption of the peace 
process in April? 
  [Al-'Anani] Jordan has always believed in the need for full 
Arab coordination to support and continue the peace process 
because Arab coordination unifies Arab stances and precludes 
unilateral measures. Some issues on the agenda on the Arab 
track are interlinked and we want to make sure that the Arab 
stances are harmonious and integrated. 
  We believe the horrible massacre of Hebron has provided 
clear 
evidence that any decision or measure affecting a single track, 
such as the Palestinian-Israeli track, is bound to have obvious 
repercussions and effects on other Arab tracks that would block 
their progress. We believe that Arab coordination 
(?strengthens) Arab stances and prevents unilateral measures and 
competition among Arab tracks at their own expense. 

</TEXT>

